tions\": [\n        \"Should be considered as the downstream portion of P1/P2 rather than a standalone pathway\",\n        \"Needs explicit upstream erythrose source\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.35,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.62,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.70,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.55,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.60,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway is significantly weakened by the speculative C-alkylation of imidazole with glycolaldehyde (rxn_012). There is no experimental precedent for this regioselective functionalization producing imidazole-4-acetaldehyde under prebiotic conditions. The Radziszewski imidazole synthesis (rxn_009) is well-supported, and the UV photooxidation of glycolaldehyde to glyoxal (rxn_005) is plausible though less characterized. The upstream hydrothermal chemistry and downstream Strecker are sound, but the speculative bridge reaction undermines the pathway's credibility.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"rxn_012 needs experimental validation - this is the single most critical unknown\",\n        \"Consider Friedel-Crafts-type alkylation conditions or metal-catalyzed alternatives\",\n        \"The regioselectivity problem (C4 vs C2 vs C5 substitution) must be addressed\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.35,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.63,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.68,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.55,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.60,\n      \"feedback\": \"Same fundamental issue as P4: the speculative rxn_012 is the critical weak link. The upstream Fischer-Tropsch entry is slightly cleaner than CO\u2082 reduction but the pathway still fails at the imidazole functionalization step. Well-conceived as an alternative but experimentally unsupported.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Same as P4 - rxn_012 requires experimental demonstration\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.92\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.92,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.40,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.70,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.0,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.30,\n      \"feedback\": \"Both reactions are individually excellent and well-supported by literature (Ferris and Orgel 1966, Ferris and Kuder 1970). HCN tetramerization to DAMN and UV photoisomerization to AICN are among the most robust reactions in prebiotic chemistry. However, this pathway explicitly does not reach histidine - it terminates at AICN, a purine precursor. The network honestly acknowledges this as a dead-end illustrating the purine-histidine biosynthetic link. While scientifically interesting and topologically valuable for the network, it cannot be evaluated as a histidine synthesis pathway.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Could potentially connect to histidine if AICN \u2192 AICA \u2192 functionalized imidazole-acetaldehyde route were developed\",\n        \"This branch enriches the network conceptually but needs future experimental work to become productive\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.78,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.65,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.76,\n      \"feedback\": \"A streamlined surface-only version of the Shen route starting from formaldehyde. Chemically sound but lacks the hydrothermal feedstock generation and requires formamidine (from rxn_007, not listed in pathway but implicitly needed for rxn_008). The missing environmental diversity is a weakness for the network evaluation criteria. All surface reactions are plausible with appropriate mineral agents (borate for formose stabilization).\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Should explicitly include rxn_007 for formamidine generation\",\n        \"Would benefit from linking to hydrothermal formaldehyde sources\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.65,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.35,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.75,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.74,\n      \"feedback\": \"An elegant convergent pathway showing glycolaldehyde as a divergent hub feeding both the erythrose branch (Shen route) and the glyoxal branch (Radziszewski route), both converging on imidazole-4-acetaldehyde. The topology is excellent and the convergence is meaningful. However, the Radziszewski branch still relies on the speculative rxn_012. The Shen b